{{hg cat}} command is executed during content indexing with filename passed as an argument and while Windows converts arguments to ANSI codepage, garbled filename gets to git process, eg:

{noformat}
> hg --config ui.verbose=false cat -r 547a7f4d4890c363836ebe7ae0bfb7e2dc421095 αφιλε.τχτ
?????.???: no such file in rev 547a7f4d4890
{noformat}

This leads to an error during indexing file content being printed to log and visible in Administration > Repository Status > Recent Errors section:
{quote}Problem indexing content of "αφιλε.τχτ" for rev "547a7f4d4890c363836ebe7ae0bfb7e2dc421095" from repo "unicode-file-names" due to class com.atlassian.fisheye.dvcs.handler.DvcsProcessException - Error while communicating with VCS: ?????.???: no such file in rev 547a7f4d4890{quote}
and also an attempt to display file content (request for /browse/unicode-file-names/%CE%B1%CF%86%CE%B9%CE%BB%CE%B5.%CF%84%CF%87%CF%84?r=547a7f4d4890c363836ebe7ae0bfb7e2dc421095) cause an error to be displayed.

Described problem occurs if file.encoding is set to UTF-8 (it's a value that we recommend user to force during fisheye startup). When run with default windows encoding (windows-1250) there are no indexing errors, file content can be displayed, but filename gets garbled:
{quote}
Î±Ď†ÎąÎ»Îµ.Ď„Ď‡Ď„
{quote}

The Crucible web UI will show lines added removed and changed, and seems to know the difference between them.  It would be great if the Fisheye/Crucible REST API could also provide this distinction.

From:

{code}
for (i =0; i < 5; i++) {
  print "Hello";
}
exit;
{code}

To:
{code}
// loop the print
for (i =0; i < 5; i++) {
  print "Hello World";
}
{code}

Summary being that one line was changed, one line was added and one line was removed:

The current [REST metrics|https://docs.atlassian.com/fisheye-crucible/latest/wadl/fisheye.html#rest-service-fe:revisionData-v1:revisionInfo:repository] would return:

{code}
    "totalLines" : 4,
    "linesAdded" : 2,
    "linesRemoved" : 2,
{code}

But what I'd like to get is:

{code}
    "totalLines" : 4,
    "linesAdded" : 1,
    "linesChanged" : 1,
    "linesRemoved" : 1,
{code}

It is possible to fake log entries in FishEye/Crucible logs, by sending specially crafted http requests containing a newline character.

For example going to the url /changelog/asd%0AFake%20log%20entry will cause the following to be logged:
{code}
2015-03-24 09:59:09,564 INFO  [qtp1610928748-315 ] fisheye ServletUtils-send404 - 404: No such repository: asd
Fake log entry referer=null
{code}

Currently in the Activity Stream whenever there is a Mercurial commit shown from Fisheye, the information displayed is pretty useless and verbose. It basically looks like this:

{code}
User Name <user.name@company.com> committed changeset ac0adc52371ffd87577f976c0a4ac27417c3123c to the project
{code}

Rather than printing the longish changeset id, I would love to see the commit message and rather than "to the project" it would be much better to have "to {repo.name}". Also of course shortening the user name would help:

{code}
User Name committed "Fixed some bugs in various files..." to test-repo.
{code}

The "committed" could be the link to the changeset.

In case where the commit is associated with a JIRA issue, a direct link to the issue would be ideal, of course.

{code}
User Name committed "Fixed some bug..." to test-repo for JRA-4242
{code}

or something like that...

